AB  - Timber harvesting intensity significantly influences forest recovery and regeneration of timber stocks. Even with reduced-impact logging (RIL), ensuring species recovery is crucial for sustainable management. This study evaluates the effects of RIL and conventional logging (CL) on forest structure, diversity, and composition in logging gaps 30 years after harvesting in a primary tropical rainforest. Data were collected from permanent plots over 30 years, including field and LiDAR measurements. Tree individuals were assessed in four forest regeneration strata: seedlings, saplings, poles, and trees in 15 logging gaps for each treatment. Field inventory examined density, floristic diversity (Hill series), and floristic composition (NMDS). LiDAR data were used to compare forest structure profiles of gaps between treatments and with managed areas, and matched them with data from natural regeneration. After 30 years, no significant differences were found between RIL and CL in overall density, commercial species, and diversity, though variations occurred in light incidence and floristic composition. Some ecological groups showed differences between treatments. Structural recovery of the gaps occurred in both logging methods, with CL gaps being smaller. Vertical leaf area profiles differed between treatments in some strata. Above-ground biomass correlated with canopy height and spatial heterogeneity, as did tree and seedling density. These results indicate that both logging methods facilitated structural, diversity, and compositional recovery in gaps. However, the low or absent regeneration of harvested species after thirty years suggests that targeted silvicultural treatments should be incorporated into management plans to enhance the sustainability of timber production in tropical forests.
