AB  - The conversion of tropical forests to agriculture has steadily increased, threatening biodiversity through various disturbances. Similarly to deforestation, forest fires are becoming more frequent and intense, hindering forest recovery by destroying seedling and seed banks, shifting regeneration to seed rain, especially through the arrival of allochthonous species. In disturbed landscapes, remnant trees serve as stepping-stones and regeneration nuclei, supporting forest regeneration. Our study assessed the role of remnant trees in facilitating seed rain during post-fire recovery in the Atlantic Forest, in southern Bahia, Brazil. We installed 90 seed traps (1 m2) across three burnt fragments, divided into three treatments: under live trees, under standing dead trees (snags), and in treeless areas. We recorded the seed rain for 12 months, and the seeds were morphotyped, measured, and categorized by dispersal syndrome. In total, 23,062 seeds were collected. The results revealed that the remnant trees positively affected total seed abundance and richness, specifically, the arrival of zoochoric seeds. However, the contribution of live trees and snags differed significantly in terms of morphospecies richness, with seed traps under live trees showing a greater number of species than those under snags. Seed diameter variation was not related to either distance to unburnt forest patches or treatment, likely due to the dominance of small seeds (93 %). Our results support the hypothesis that the remnant trees positively influence the seed rain in burnt areas, probably acting as regeneration nuclei. Although snags are less effective, they remain valuable for regeneration and should be preserved in post-fire management.
