AB  - Riparian forests have an important role in the maintenance of environmental services and in the conservation of species, playing the role of genetic corridor for flora and fauna. The present study was conducted with the objective of analyzing the species composition and horizontal structure in a restored riparian forest with an adjacent native area, in the municipality of Poco Fundo, Minas Gerais. A floristic and phytosociological survey of the tree sinusia was carried out in the areas. We sampled 199 individuals and 24 species in the restored area and 105 individuals and 23 species in the native area. No floristic similarity was verified between the areas. Shannon diversity was low in both areas. In the restored area, there is a predominance of early species while in the native area there is a predominance of late species. No floristic convergence was verified between the two studied areas, having been verified structural convergence between the areas after 13 years of the beginning of the restoration.
